%I A394051 #54 Apr 10 2026 11:27:22
%S A394051 1,1,1,3,3,3,5,5,5,7,5,9,7,9,7,11,9,11,11,11,13,11,15,13,15,13,17,13,
%T A394051 19,15,19,17,19,17,21,19,21,21,21,23,21,25,21,27,23,27,23,29,23,31,23,
%U A394051 33,25,33,25,35,27,35,29,35,29,37,29,39,31,39,31,41,33,41,35,41,37,41
%N A394051 Hofstadter Q-sequence perturbed by (-1)^n.
%C A394051 All terms are odd.
%C A394051 Numerical evidence suggests that a(n) ~ n/2.
%C A394051 The sequence does not terminate for all n <= 3*10^10 (verified computationally).
%C A394051 The differences a(n+1)-a(n) exhibit a dyadic, self-similar pattern on a logarithmic scale.
%H A394051 Marco Mantovanelli, <a href="/A394051/b394051.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..2000</a>
%H A394051 Benoit Cloitre, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.06237">On a perturbed Hofstadter Q-recursion</a>, arXiv:2604.06237 [math.NT], 2026.
%H A394051 Marco Mantovanelli, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.16111">Dyadic Self-Similarity in a Perturbed Hofstadter Q-Recursion</a>, arXiv:2603.16111 [math.CO], 2026.
%H A394051 Marco Mantovanelli, <a href="/A394051/a394051.pdf">Preprint: Dyadic Self-Similarity in a Perturbed Hofstadter Q-Recursion</a>.
%H A394051 Marco Mantovanelli, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.29622">A Finite-State Proof of the Well-Definedness of a Perturbed Hofstadter Sequence</a>, arXiv:2603.29622 [math.CO], 2026. See p. 2.
%F A394051 a(1)=a(2)=1; for n > 2: a(n) = a(n-a(n-1)) + a(n-a(n-2)) + (-1)^n.
%F A394051 a(n)/n = 1/2 + O(1/sqrt(log(n))). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 03 2026
%F A394051 More precisely it can be proved that limsup_{n->oo} sqrt(log_2(n)) * |a(n)/n - 1/2| = 1/(3*sqrt(2*Pi)). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 08 2026
%t A394051 Q[1] = 1; Q[2] = 1;
%t A394051 Q[n_Integer?Positive] := Q[n] = Q[n - Q[n - 1]] + Q[n - Q[n - 2]] + (-1)^n;
%t A394051 Table[Q[n], {n, 1, 350}]
%Y A394051 Cf. A005185.
%K A394051 nonn,look
%O A394051 1,4
%A A394051 _Marco Mantovanelli_, Mar 08 2026
